	 London, Sept. 5 (PTI): Several British firms and industry leaders have asked the David Cameron government to drop the policy to place an annual cap on immigration from India and other non-EU nations as the move will threaten the countrys economic recovery and force companies to relocate abroad.          
	The deadline for public consultation on the coalition governments policy ends on Tuesday.          
	The Migration Advisory Committee of the Home Office is expected to announce, later this year, the number at which immigrants from India and other non-EU countries would be capped annually.          don First, a business membership group, has urged the government to continue with the current points-based immigration system. It claims that the new policy will affect only 55,000 of the 567,000 migrants who came to the UK, based on last years figures.                  
	 Mumbai: A campaign by supporters of the Shiv Sena and the MNS to unite the Thackeray cousins fell flat on Sunday as neither leader showed any interest. The Thackeray jodo (unite the Thackerays) march by their well-wishers from both camps started from outside Maharashtra Navnirman Sena chief Raj Thackerays home in Shivaji Park but the leader was not present at that time. The marchers, led by Sena activist Satish Walanju and former Sena MLA Suresh Gambhir, went to Matoshri, Sena patrirach Bal Thackerays home. His son and Rajs cousin, Uddhav, met them but told them he had no plans to mend fences with Raj.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Central Administrative Tribunal has held that government employees on the verge of retirement should not be transfered merely because they have stayed for a considerably long period at a particular place. The tribunal said that such a benefit should be given to employees about to retire after years of dedicated service.                   
	 Balasore (PTI): The 290km range BrahMos cruise missile was successfully test-fired on Sunday from the Integrated Test Range, Chandipur, off the Orissa coast as part of trials by the army.                                                                                                                                              
